":"1185","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","ABT 1250":"about 1250","ABT 1272":"about 1272","1215":"1215","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","ABT 1255":"about 1255","1255":"1255","1265":"1265","Verneix,03305,Allier,Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes,FRANCE,Mirebeau":"Verneix, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France","Mirebeau (60)":"Mirebeau, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","Bommiers, Indre, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Bommiers, Indre, Centre-Val de Loire, France","Charenton-le-Pont,94018,Val-de-Marne,Île-de-France,FRANCE,":"Charenton-le-Pont, Val-de-Marne, Île-de-France, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"BEAUMIERS","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Lucien, Cecile, Gaston, Jacques, Valmont, Yves.","French Canadian: altered form of French <b>Boesmé</b> or <b>Boismé</b>, a habitational name from Boismé, a place in Deux-Sèvres. The surnames <i>Boesmé</i> and <i>Boismé</i> are very rare or extinct, respectively, in France. Compare   Boismier  ,   Bomia  , and   Bomier  .","In some cases possibly also French: variant of <b>Baumier</b>, a topographic name derived from <i>baume</i>, a regional form of <i>balme</i> ‘cave’."],"variants":[{"name":"Boismier","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French Canadian: altered form of French <b>Boesmé</b> or <b>Boismé</b> (see   Beaumier  )."]},{"name":"Bomier","meanings":["(2010: NA)","Americanized form of French Canadian   Beaumier  . Compare   Bomia  .","In some cases possibly also French: derivative of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bonmar</i>, composed of the elements <i>bon</i> ‘good’ (from Latin <i>bonus</i>) and <i>mar</i> ‘famous’. This surname is very rare in France."]},{"name":"Bomia","meanings":["Americanized form of French Canadian   Beaumier  . Compare   Bomier  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["probably a contracted form of  Jep , vernacular form of   Jacob   ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert IV de BEAUMIERS was born about 1215, in Verneix, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France, his father, Robert III de Bommiers - Seigneur de Mirebeau, was 18 and his mother, Marguerite DE BLAISON MIREBEAU, was 31. He married Mahaut de CHAUVIGNY about 1248. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died about 1272, in his hometown, at the age of 59."},"et":{"ABT 1215–ABT 1272":"umbes 1215–umbes 1272","1215–1272":"1215–1272","1230–1323":"1230–1323","1250–1322":"1250–1322","1250–1323":"1250–1323","1255–1295":"1255–1295","1198–1265":"1198–1265","1185–1252":"1185–1252","1198":"1198","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","ABT 1215":"umbes 1215","ABT 1248":"umbes 1248","1185":"1185","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","ABT 1250":"umbes 1250","ABT 1272":"umbes 1272","1215":"1215","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","ABT 1255":"umbes 1255","1255":"1255","1265":"1265","Verneix,03305,Allier,Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes,FRANCE,Mirebeau":"Verneix, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa","Mirebeau (60)":"Mirebeau, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Bommiers, Indre, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Bommiers, Indre, Centre-Val de Loire, Prantsusmaa","Charenton-le-Pont,94018,Val-de-Marne,Île-de-France,FRANCE,":"Charenton-le-Pont, Val-de-Marne, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"ABT 1215–ABT 1272":"noin 1215–noin 1272","1215–1272":"1215–1272","1230–1323":"1230–1323","1250–1322":"1250–1322","1250–1323":"1250–1323","1255–1295":"1255–1295","1198–1265":"1198–1265","1185–1252":"1185–1252","1198":"1198","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","ABT 1215":"noin 1215","ABT 1248":"noin 1248","1185":"1185","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","ABT 1250":"noin 1250","ABT 1272":"noin 1272","1215":"1215","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","ABT 1255":"noin 1255","1255":"1255","1265":"1265","Verneix,03305,Allier,Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes,FRANCE,Mirebeau":"Verneix, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Ranska","Mirebeau (60)":"Mirebeau, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Ranska","Bommiers, Indre, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Bommiers, Indre, Centre-Val de Loire, Ranska","Charenton-le-Pont,94018,Val-de-Marne,Île-de-France,FRANCE,":"Charenton-le-Pont, Val-de-Marne, Île-de-France, Ranska","France":